	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>The debate on EU sugar-sector reform</h1>

			
			<h4>
												22 September 2004
										</h4>

					</header>


				<div class="intro">

						<p> The EC proposals for sugar-sector reform were published in July 2004 and basically amount to adoption (as expected) of the ‘fall in price’ option. In presenting the case for sugar-sector reform, Commissioner Fischler advanced two reasons for tackling the problem now. First the need to prepare the EU sugar sector for the arrival of zero-tariff EBA sugar as from July 1st 2009, since if this is not done ‘the EU sugar sector will enter into an attrition scenario, in which even our best producing areas will have to dramatically reduce production’. Second the need to bring the sugar sector into line with the main trajectory of the CAP. He argued that leaving sugar out of the reform process would ‘be an act of irresponsibility’.</p>

		</div>
		
		
					<p> The Commission proposals were received with mixed feelings by EU member states with opinions ranging from ‘too fast, too early’ to a ‘bold proposal and a step in the right direction’. However, despite the wide divergence of views between member states on the specifics of the proposals for reform, there was unanimity on the inevitability of reform of the sugar regime. The proposals were referred back for further discussion at the technical level, with the Council expected to draw up a review of the outcome of the first round of discussions in November 2004.</p><p> In his presentation of the reforms Commissioner Fischler stressed that any reform has to be ‘consistent with the EU’s international commitments, in particular the EBA and ACP agreements’. At a press conference he committed the EU to working with ACP countries to define appropriate trade and development measures for countries adversely affected by the proposed reforms before the end of 2004. The Commission is envisaging tailor-made programmes to help affected ACP countries ‘adapt to the new market conditions to improve the competitiveness of sugar production where viable’ and where it is not viable to support diversification.</p><p> The ICTSD noted that the Commission proposal will have far-reaching impacts on domestic EU production, with non-competitive sugar-growing areas likely to see production disappearing. EU farmers and processors will however be partially compensated for the income losses arising from price reductions. Ireland and the Nordic countries were the most vocal critics of the Commission proposals, claiming that they would simply hand the EU market over to Brazil.</p><p> ACP sugar-exporting countries have also been fiercely critical of the Commission proposals, since they will face major income losses without any of the compensation that EU farmers and processors will receive.</p><p> The UK sugar traders’ website reports assessments by Merril Lynch that ‘the EU plan may reduce the profits of Sudzucker AG, Tate and Lyle and Danisco by 30% in the next three years’. However in its statement British Sugar said ‘as one of the most efficient producers in Europe, British Sugar is well placed to meet the challenges of reform and to take advantage of any opportunities it may offer’.</p><p> CEFS (the European sugar processors’ association) welcomed the Commission’s commitment to a managed sugar regime but expressed the belief that this should be extended to cover EBA sugar within a quota-managed system. A quota-managed system is also favoured by the ACP since it would support the EU sugar price.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			

<ul>

<li> 
<a href="http://europa.eu.int/comm/agriculture/capreform/sugarprop_en.pdf" target="_self">Text of the EC communication (COM(2004)499 final-14/07/2004)</a> </li>

<li> 
<a href="http://europa.eu.int/rapid/pressReleasesAction.do?reference=IP/04/915&amp;format=HTML&amp;aged=0&amp;language=EN&amp;guiLanguage=en" target="_self">EC press release (IP/04/915-14/07/2004)</a> </li>

<li> 
<a href="http://europa.eu.int/rapid/pressReleasesAction.do?reference=MEMO/04/177&amp;format=HTML&amp;aged=0&amp;language=EN&amp;guiLanguage=en" target="_self">EC memorandum (MEMO/04/177-14/07/2004)</a> </li>

<li> 
<a href="http://europa.eu.int/rapid/pressReleasesAction.do?reference=SPEECH/04/363&amp;format=HTML&amp;aged=0&amp;language=EN&amp;guiLanguage=en" target="_self">Speech by Commissioner Fischler (SPEECH/04/363-14/07/2004)</a> </li>

<li> 
<a href="http://www.ictsd.org/biores/04-07-23/story2.htm" target="_self">Extended ICTSD report (Vol. 4, No. 14, July 23 rd 2004)</a> </li>

<li> 
<a href="http://www.fas.usda.gov/gainfiles/200407/146106832.pdf" target="_self">USDA GAIN Report (GAIN Report No. E34033)</a> </li>

<li> 
