</ul>
		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> The EC is firmly opposed to a ‘fixed quota’ system, believing that this would freeze the current anomalies of the sugar regime, whereby production has been encouraged in the least cost-efficient areas and discouraged in the most cost-efficient areas. It wants to see a radical restructuring of the EU sugar sector to enhance its competitiveness and significantly reduce average sugar costs.</p><p> In terms of the impact of the proposed reforms on the ACP and the scope for restructuring assistance, studies financed by the UK Department for International Development have set out a range of options for affected ACP sugar exporters. These include:</p>
<ul>

<li>compensation: straight financial compensation for the loss of the value of preferences; </li>

<li>improving competitiveness: financial assistance to assist the sugar industry in lowering production costs, increasing competitiveness and ensuring profitability; </li>

<li>diversification and exit: assistance to support the development of alternative crops and sector, and to finance an orderly closure or partial closure of the sugar industry; </li>

<li>poverty mitigation: provision of safety nets and social services targeted at those groups most adversely affected by the loss of preferences. </li>

</ul>
<p> The study divided ACP sugar producers into three distinct categories in terms of the consequences of sugar-sector reform:</p>
<ul>

<li>Group 1 sugar industries where production remains profitable; </li>

<li>Group 2 sugar industries where restructuring is necessary; </li>

<li>Group 3 sugar industries which do not have a profitable future. </li>

</ul>
<p> According to the DfID study the Caribbean would be most severely affected by EU sugar-sector reform, with the sugar sector disappearing in most traditional sugar-supplying countries, with the direct loss of around 100,000 jobs.</p><p> While the Commission has highlighted the support it is willing to give to enhance the competitiveness of ACP sugar production, the experience of such programmes in the banana sector offers little hope to Caribbean sugar-producing countries. While the EU is committed to supporting diversification where improving competitiveness is not possible, it is difficult to see into what areas diversification could take place in the Caribbean, with the banana, rice, and rum sectors all suffering the effects of EU policy changes.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
	</article>

